    <h1>It&#x2019;s clear, glass keeps food fresh</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201218/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-18"><time>2020-12-18</time></a>
        - <span>SINGAPORE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Glass jars help pre­serve the fresh­ness of cer­tain herbs and spices, says ONE FM 91.3 DJ An­gelique Teo. They keep chilli padi, her go-to spice, fresh and ready to eat. Her se­cret: wash, dice, place them in glass jars and keep frozen to help them last longer. The av­er­age house­hold in Sin­ga­pore throws out about $258 worth of un­eaten food each year. The Sun­day Times gets to the bot­tom of the is­sue, and raids fridges to see how some homes are re­duc­ing wastage.</p>

